title: A study of the giant dipole states of Si-28, S-32 and Ca-40.

x4freetext: A 0.025 cm thick tungsten target was used.
The flight path = 42 m.
The  photoneutrons  were  detected  in  30  cm
diameter  * 7.6 cm thick plastic scintillator (pilot
b), viewed by two 12.7 cm  diameter  amperex  58 avp
phototubes  operating  in coincidence.  The detector
threshold was 0.6 MeV with 0.10 MeV error
The cylindrical targets of 7.6 cm diameter and 6.3 mm
thickness were used.
The ground   state   yields  were  deduced  from  the
differences  between  the  measurements  of  neutron
spectra  at  the  different end-point energies.  The
end-point energy  step  was  less  than  the  energy
spacing  between the ground and first excited states
of the residual nuclei.  The  energy  resolution  of
time-of  flight method was equated to 7 keV at 1 MeV
neutron energy and 60 kev at 4 MeV neutron energy.
The differential   cross   section   for  the  (g,n0)
reactions on  Si-28 ,  S-32   and  Ca-40  have  been
measured.  Pronounced  structure  is observed in the
three  reactions  at   excitation   energies   which
correspond to the giant dipole resonance region. The
results are compared with (p,g0) and (g,p0) data  to
test  whether  or  not the cross sections are due to
resonances or statistical fluctuations and to  study
possible isospin mixing effects. Strong correlations
are observed  between  the  energies  and  width  of
intermediate-type    structure    in    all    three
cases. Pseudo cross-section  calculations  have also
been carried out using the Thomas reduced r-function
theory to generate fluctuations and the results then
compared with the experimental data. It is concluded
that in Si-28 the  cross  section  is  dominated  by
fluctuations  whereas  in  s-32  and  Ca-40 there is
evidence supporting some resolved resonance effects.

end-point energies of 19 and 21 MeV.
Data were  corrected  for  the  background   due   to
isotopic impurities of Si-29 and Si-30.
